Since $M$ and $N$ are midpoints, $M$ and $N$ are the averages of $A$ and $B,$ and $A$ and $C,$ respectively.  Hence,
\[M = \left( \frac{6 + 0}{2}, \frac{0 + 4}{2} \right) = (3,2)\]and
\[N = \left( \frac{6 + 0}{2}, \frac{0 + 0}{2} \right) = (3,0).\]Since $MN$ is parallel to the $x$-axis, the equation of line $MN$ is $x = 3.$  Since $O$ lies on line $MN,$ $O$ has the form $(3,y,z).$

Since $O$ is the center of the sphere, $OA = OD = r,$ so
\[\sqrt{(3 - 6)^2 + (y - 0)^2 + (z - 0)^2} = r.\]Also, $O$ lies on the plane determined by $ABC,$ so
\[0 = \begin{vmatrix} 3 & 2 & 0 \\ 6 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 4 & 0 \end{vmatrix} = 12.\]Hence, $O$ lies on the line $x = 3,$ so $O = (3,y,z).$  Then
\[\sqrt{(3 - 6)^2 + (y - 0)^2 + (z - 0)^2} = r.\]Squaring both sides, we get
\[9 + y^2 + z^2 = r^2.\]Since $O$ lies on the plane determined by $ABC,$ $O$ satisfies the equation of this plane, which is
\[\begin{vmatrix} 3 & 2 & 0 \\ 6 & 0 & 0 \\ 0 & 4 & 0 \end{vmatrix} = 0.\]This gives us $12 = 0,$ contradiction.  Hence, there is no such sphere.

