Since $x^2 + bx + b$ is a factor of $x^3 + 2x^2 + 2x + c,$ the polynomial $x^3 + 2x^2 + 2x + c$ must be divisible by $x^2 + bx + b.$  In other words, the remainder when $x^3 + 2x^2 + 2x + c$ is divided by $x^2 + bx + b$ must be 0.

We can use polynomial long division to find this remainder:
\[
\begin{array}{c|cc cc}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{x} & + 2 \\
\cline{2-5}
x^2 + bx + b & x^3 & + 2x^2 & + 2x & + c \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{-x^3} & -bx^2 & -bx \\
\cline{2-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{0} & (2 - b)x^2 & (2 - b)x & + c \\
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & -(2 - b)x^2 & -(2 - b)x \\
\cline{3-4}
\multicolumn{2}{r}{} & 0 & c
\end{array}
\]Thus, the remainder is $c.$  Hence, $c = 0,$ so the possible values of $b$ are $\boxed{2}.$

