By the Law of Sines on triangles $ABD,$ $ADE,$ and $AEC,$
\begin{align*}
\frac{BD}{\sin x} &= \frac{AB}{\sin (180^\circ - x - y)}, \\
\frac{DE}{\sin y} &= \frac{AD}{\sin (180^\circ - x - y)}, \\
\frac{EC}{\sin z} &= \frac{AE}{\sin (180^\circ - y - z)}.
\end{align*}Since $\angle ABD = \angle ADE = \angle AEC = 180^\circ - x - y,$
\[\frac{AB}{\sin (180^\circ - x - y)} = \frac{AD}{\sin (180^\circ - x - y)} = \frac{AE}{\sin (180^\circ - y - z)}.\]Then
\[\frac{BD}{\sin x} = \frac{DE}{\sin y} = \frac{EC}{\sin z}.\]By the Law of Sines on triangle $ABC,$
\[\frac{BC}{\sin A} = \frac{AB}{\sin C} = \frac{AC}{\sin B}.\]Since $\angle ABD = \angle ADE = \angle AEC = 180^\circ - x - y,$
\[\frac{BC}{\sin (x + y)} = \frac{AB}{\sin (180^\circ - x - y)} = \frac{AC}{\sin (180^\circ - x - y)}.\]Then
\[\frac{BC}{\sin (x + y)} = \frac{BD}{\sin x} = \frac{DE}{\sin y} = \frac{EC}{\sin z}.\]Hence,
\[\frac{\sin (x + y) \sin (y + z)}{\sin x \sin z} = \boxed{1}.\]

